#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
int main() {
    int x = 4;
    int* p = &x;
    cout << p << endl;
    p++;
    cout << p << endl;
    cout << *p;
}

//output

//000000E80D13FD24
//000000E80D13FD28
//- 858993460

//000000C8E190FCF4
//000000C8E190FCF8
//- 858993460

----
Stack memory initialization in debug mode
----

-> Many compilers (MSVC, for example) fill uninitialized stack memory with a fixed pattern when running in debug mode.

-> On Windows, the pattern 0xCCCCCCCC (or -858993460 in decimal) is commonly used.

-> This is intentional to help detect bugs like using uninitialized variables or accessing freed memory.

